article.description: Tina Charles scored 17 points and helped No. 1 Connecticut remain unbeaten with a 80-61 victory over Georgetown on Saturday.
article.headline: No. 1 Huskies pull away to remain undefeated
article.linkText: UConn fights off scrappy G'town to stay perfect
article.story:
WASHINGTON -- It wasn't the sort of blowout that's become routine for No. 1 Connecticut. Still the Huskies remained unbeaten after 21 games and had the game well in hand early in the second half.

Tina Charles scored 17 points and UConn, which trailed with 6 1/2 minutes left in the first half, used a 21-0 run in the second half to take control of a 80-61 win Saturday afternoon.

The game was far closer than most Connecticut has played this season. The Huskies entered the game winning by an average of 34 points, including eight wins of 40 points or more.

"Not every game is going to be a masterpiece," UConn coach Geno Auriemma said.

Connecticut (21-0, 7-0 Big East), which has held the No. 1 spot since the preseason, won its first 21 games for the second straight season. A win against Rutgers at home Tuesday would give the Huskies their best start since winning the first 31 games in 2002-03. It is also the fifth straight season UConn has started 7-0 in conference play.

Once Connecticut's offense got on a roll, nearly everyone for the Huskies joined in. For the 10th time this season, UConn had five players in double figures. Along with Charles, Tiffany Hayes, Renee Montgomery and Maya Moore each scored 14, and Kalana Greene had 10.

"I think that's the goal of every coach, to coach a team with so many options," Auriemma said. "It's just a matter of trying to get them all in sync at the same time."

Karee Houlette led the Hoyas with 20 points, and Adria Crawford had her third double-double of the season with 13 points and 10 rebounds.

Georgetown (13-8, 3-5) has not beaten Connecticut since Feb. 27, 1993, a streak of 22 losses. The Hoyas had lost all the previous three meeting by at least 32 points, but Saturday Georgetown kept the margin down with its 3-point shooting.

The Hoyas were 10-of-20 on 3s, led by Houlette's 6-for-10 performance. Houlette, however, had to be helped off the court with 2:55 left after injuring her left ankle, and Georgetown coach Terri Williams-Flournoy did not know the extent of the injury.

Georgetown was already without leading scorer Jaleesa Butler, who suffered an ankle injury Wednesday in the Hoyas' 50-39 loss to No. 21 Pittsburgh. Williams-Flournoy called her status day-to-day, but Butler sat on the bench in street clothes Saturday.

She and a sold-out crowd of 2,413 -- evenly split between UConn and Hoya fans -- watched Butler's teammates give Connecticut a surprisingly tough time through most of the first half.

Georgetown won the opening tip and Crawford made a layup on the opening possession, the first indication the Hoyas weren't going to roll over for the top-ranked Huskies.

The Hoyas held the lead as late as 6 1/2 minutes to go in the first half, when Houlette hit a 3-pointer -- her fourth of the half -- to put Georgetown up 25-24.

"You're playing the No. 1 team the country and you're up -- and I'm telling them there's a lot of time left," Williams-Flournoy said. "But you can't help but be excited. We lose by 19, and it might be one of the best losses from the teams that have played them."

The Huskies uncharacteristically made mistakes on offense and occasionally fell victim to the Hoyas' aggressive defense early, committing 12 turnovers in the first half. UConn's 23 turnovers in the game were a season high.

"Sometimes we get in trouble a lot for overpassing," Montgomery said. "Somebody is trying to make a play or make somebody catch the ball when we could just shoot it. We're trying to do too much when it should be simple."

However, Connecticut restored order and pulled away in the final minutes of the half, closing with a 13-2 run that gave them a 45-30 halftime lead. The key play in the late surge was a four-point play by Montgomery, who made a 3-pointer from five feet behind the line despite being knocked over by the Hoyas' Meredith Cox.

Connecticut continued the run after halftime. Starting with 18:15 left, the Huskies scored 21 points while holding Georgetown scoreless for nearly nine minutes.

"It was really important for us to set the tone," Charles said, "and show that we wanted it more."

The run gave Connecticut a 70-33 lead, and the Huskies cruised the rest of the way.

"We know that we can't blow teams out as soon as we start the game," Montgomery said. "Every team we play comes out with the most intensity they'll probably have all year."
